1. The essential feature of chronic fatigue syndrome is persistent or relapsing fatigue that is of new onset, is not the result of ongoing exertion, is not substantially alleviated by rest, and results in significant reduction in previous levels of occupational, educational, social, or personal activities.
2. Four or more of the following symptoms must be present during at least six consecutive months of illness and must not have been caused by ongoing exertion:
a) Postexertional malaise lasting more than 24 hours after a predefined increase in physical or mental activity;
b) Unrefreshing sleep or sleep that is disrupted by difficulty falling asleep or staying asleep;
c) Headaches of a new type, pattern, or severity;
d) Myalgia without significant muscle weakness;
e) Arthralgia without significant joint swelling or redness;
f) Sore throat that is frequent or recurring;
g) Tender cervical or axillary lymph nodes;
h) Multiple daily headaches;
i) Raynaud's phenomenon;
j) Photophobia;
k) Paresthesias.
